The different models were compared using a fivefold cross validation scheme. Briefly, all genotyped and phenotyped animals were randomly separated into five validations sets, which were predicted one at a time by masking their phenotypes and using the remaining animals as training set to estimate the marker effects. Thus, for each validation run, the dataset was split into a training set (80%) and a validation set (20%). To reduce the stochastic effects, this cross-validation analysis was replicated 10 times. Accuracy was used to assess the performance of each model and was estimated as:\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
